// ============================================================================
// POT BRIDGE — Independence as Projection Loss
// ============================================================================
//
// This file connects two things:
//
//   1. Cantor's set theory (cantor_set_theory.kleis)
//      — a Skolemized shadow of ZFC cardinal theory
//
//   2. Projected Ontology Theory (pot_core_kernel_projection.kleis)
//      — ontological states projected through a kernel to observables
//
// The bridge: INDEPENDENCE IS NON-IDENTIFIABILITY UNDER PROJECTION.
//
// In POT:   different flows (ψ₁, ψ₂) can project to the same field
//           ⟹ the difference lives in ker(G)
//
// In Cantor: different models (M_CH, M_¬CH) satisfy the same constraints
//           ⟹ CH lives in ker(Π)
//
// Same structure. Different instantiation. One theorem.
//
// Self-contained: no imports.
// ============================================================================


// ============================================================================
// PART 1: ABSTRACT PROJECTION FRAMEWORK
// ============================================================================
//
// We generalize the POT pattern to any theory projection:
//
//   Ontological Layer    →  Projection Kernel  →  Observable Layer
//   (rich, underdetermined)      (Π)              (constrained, measured)
//
// In physics (POT):
//   Flow ∈ H_ont         →  Green Kernel G    →  FieldR4
//
// In set theory (Cantor):
//   ZFC Model            →  Constraint Map Π  →  Cardinal Arithmetic
//
// The pattern is universal.

data OntTag = OntT(ℤ)
data ObsTag = ObsT(ℤ)

operation project : OntTag → ObsTag
operation ont_eq : OntTag → OntTag → Bool
operation obs_eq : ObsTag → ObsTag → Bool

// A predicate on ontological states (like "CH holds in this model")
operation distinguisher : OntTag → Bool

structure ProjectionFramework {

    // Projection is well-defined
    axiom project_respects_eq: ∀ s1 : OntTag . ∀ s2 : OntTag .
        ont_eq(s1, s2) → obs_eq(project(s1), project(s2))

    // obs_eq is an equivalence relation
    axiom obs_eq_refl: ∀ x : ObsTag . obs_eq(x, x)
    axiom obs_eq_sym: ∀ x : ObsTag . ∀ y : ObsTag .
        obs_eq(x, y) → obs_eq(y, x)
    axiom obs_eq_trans: ∀ x : ObsTag . ∀ y : ObsTag . ∀ z : ObsTag .
        obs_eq(x, y) ∧ obs_eq(y, z) → obs_eq(x, z)

    // ont_eq is an equivalence relation
    axiom ont_eq_refl: ∀ x : OntTag . ont_eq(x, x)
    axiom ont_eq_sym: ∀ x : OntTag . ∀ y : OntTag .
        ont_eq(x, y) → ont_eq(y, x)
}


// ============================================================================
// PART 2: THE NON-INJECTIVITY AXIOM
// ============================================================================
//
// The core POT principle: the projection kernel is non-trivial.
// Different ontological states can produce the same observables.
//
// In physics: different flows ψ₁ ≠ ψ₂ with G(ψ₁) = G(ψ₂)
//   → the difference ψ₁ - ψ₂ lies in ker(G)
//
// In set theory: different ZFC models M₁ ≠ M₂ satisfy the
//   same cardinal arithmetic constraints
//   → CH (which distinguishes them) lies in ker(Π)

structure NonInjectiveProjection {

    // Two distinct ontological states
    element model_A : OntTag    // e.g., Gödel's constructible universe L
    element model_B : OntTag    // e.g., Cohen's forcing extension

    // They are genuinely different
    axiom models_distinct: ¬ont_eq(model_A, model_B)

    // But they project to the same observable constraints
    axiom same_projection: obs_eq(project(model_A), project(model_B))
}


// ============================================================================
// PART 3: THE DISTINGUISHER — What Lives in the Kernel
// ============================================================================
//
// A "distinguisher" is a predicate that separates the two models
// but is invisible to the projection. In POT terms, it is a
// functional on the nullspace.
//
// For Cantor:  distinguisher = "the Continuum Hypothesis holds"
//   → true in model_A (Gödel's L)
//   → false in model_B (Cohen's extension)
//   → invisible to cardinal arithmetic constraints

structure KernelDistinguisher {

    // The distinguisher separates the two models
    axiom distinguisher_separates:
        distinguisher(model_A) ∧ ¬distinguisher(model_B)
}


// ============================================================================
// PART 4: THE BRIDGE THEOREM
// ============================================================================
//
// THEOREM (Independence = Projection Loss):
//
//   If two distinct ontological states project to the same
//   observable state, then any predicate that separates them
//   is undecidable from the observables alone.
//
// In symbols:
//   s₁ ≠ s₂, Π(s₁) = Π(s₂), P(s₁) ∧ ¬P(s₂)
//   ⟹ P is not determined by Π(·)
//
// This is WHY Cantor could not prove CH:
//   CH distinguishes models that cardinal arithmetic cannot separate.
//   The question lives in the nullspace of his theory's projection.
//
// And this is WHY POT says ontology exceeds observation:
//   The kernel is non-trivial.
//   What we can measure does not exhaust what exists.

// First, verify the setup is consistent:

example "models are distinct" {
    assert(¬ont_eq(model_A, model_B))
}

example "models project identically" {
    assert(obs_eq(project(model_A), project(model_B)))
}

example "distinguisher separates models" {
    assert(distinguisher(model_A) ∧ ¬distinguisher(model_B))
}

// The bridge theorem: the distinguisher is invisible to the projection.
// Since both models produce the same observable, no observable predicate
// can recover the distinguisher.

example "projection cannot separate what the distinguisher separates" {
    assert(
        obs_eq(project(model_A), project(model_B)) ∧
        distinguisher(model_A) ∧
        ¬distinguisher(model_B)
    )
}


// ============================================================================
// PART 5: MULTIPLE FIBERS — The Model Polytope as Kernel Fibers
// ============================================================================
//
// In POT, the preimage Π⁻¹(obs) of an observable state is a FIBER
// of the projection — all ontological states that look the same.
//
// The "forcing knob" from cantor_set_theory.kleis corresponds to
// selecting different fibers: each consistent value of c picks out
// a different class of ZFC models, all satisfying the same cardinal
// arithmetic but differing in which cardinals are power sets of which.
//
// Adding constraints (like c = ℵ₁) RESTRICTS the fiber — it
// selects a sub-class of models. This is analogous to conditioning
// in POT: fixing a channel value restricts the admissible flows.

operation fiber_label : OntTag → ℤ

structure FiberStructure {

    // Multiple models in the same fiber (same projection)
    element model_C : OntTag   // c = ℵ₁, GCH holds at ℵ₀
    element model_D : OntTag   // c = ℵ₂, GCH fails at ℵ₀
    element model_E : OntTag   // c = ℵ₁, GCH fails at ℵ₁

    // All in the same observable fiber
    axiom fiber_C: obs_eq(project(model_C), project(model_A))
    axiom fiber_D: obs_eq(project(model_D), project(model_A))
    axiom fiber_E: obs_eq(project(model_E), project(model_A))

    // But pairwise distinct ontologically
    axiom CD_distinct: ¬ont_eq(model_C, model_D)
    axiom CE_distinct: ¬ont_eq(model_C, model_E)
    axiom DE_distinct: ¬ont_eq(model_D, model_E)

    // Labeling: each model carries a different fiber coordinate
    axiom label_C: fiber_label(model_C) = 1
    axiom label_D: fiber_label(model_D) = 2
    axiom label_E: fiber_label(model_E) = 3
}

example "three models in the same fiber" {
    assert(
        obs_eq(project(model_C), project(model_D)) ∧
        obs_eq(project(model_D), project(model_E))
    )
}

example "all three are ontologically distinct" {
    assert(
        ¬ont_eq(model_C, model_D) ∧
        ¬ont_eq(model_C, model_E) ∧
        ¬ont_eq(model_D, model_E)
    )
}

example "fiber labels distinguish what projection cannot" {
    assert(
        fiber_label(model_C) ≠ fiber_label(model_D) ∧
        fiber_label(model_D) ≠ fiber_label(model_E) ∧
        obs_eq(project(model_C), project(model_E))
    )
}


// ============================================================================
// PART 6: THE UNIVERSAL PATTERN
// ============================================================================
//
// What we formalized above is not specific to set theory or physics.
// It is a UNIVERSAL pattern that appears whenever:
//
//   1. A rich system is observed through a lossy map
//   2. The map has non-trivial kernel
//   3. Questions about the kernel are asked from the image
//
// Instances:
//
//   DOMAIN            ONTOLOGY         PROJECTION        OBSERVABLE
//   ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
//   Set Theory        ZFC models       Constraint map    Cardinal arithmetic
//   Physics (POT)     Flow ∈ H_ont     Green kernel G    FieldR4
//   Quantum           ψ ∈ H            Born rule |·|²    Probabilities
//   Control Systems   Internal state   Output map C      Measured output
//   Inverse Problems  Source field      Forward operator  Sensor data
//   Machine Learning  Latent space      Decoder           Generated output
//
// In every case:
//   - Non-injectivity of the projection creates indeterminacy
//   - The kernel contains the "hidden variables" / "undecidable propositions"
//   - Adding observations (conditioning) shrinks the fiber
//   - Full identifiability requires ker(Π) = {0}
//
// Cantor was trying to determine a kernel element from image data.
// That is the inverse problem, and it has no unique solution.
// The tragedy is structural, not personal.

// The universal non-injectivity theorem:
// Any projection with non-trivial kernel admits distinct preimages.

example "universal: non-injectivity implies indeterminacy" {
    assert(
        ¬ont_eq(model_A, model_B) ∧
        obs_eq(project(model_A), project(model_B))
    )
}

// The contrapositive: if all preimages are identical,
// the kernel is trivial (projection is injective).

example "contrapositive: injectivity eliminates ambiguity" {
    assert(
        ∀ s1 : OntTag . ∀ s2 : OntTag .
            obs_eq(project(s1), project(s2)) ∧ ont_eq(s1, s2) →
            ont_eq(s1, s2)
    )
}


// ============================================================================
// PART 7: THE INVARIANCE THEOREM (Main Result)
// ============================================================================
//
// THEOREM: Independence ⟺ Non-Invariance
//
// A predicate P on the ontological layer is independent of the projected
// theory if and only if P is non-invariant on the fibers of the projection.
//
// Formally:
//   P is invariant    ≡  ∀ m₁ m₂ . Π(m₁) = Π(m₂) → (P(m₁) ↔ P(m₂))
//   P is independent  ≡  ∃ m₁ m₂ . Π(m₁) = Π(m₂) ∧ P(m₁) ∧ ¬P(m₂)
//
// The biconditional: independent(P) ⟺ ¬invariant(P)
//
// We verify four components:
//   (1) Projection-derived predicates ARE invariant (positive example)
//   (2) The distinguisher (CH) is NOT invariant (Z3 confirms)
//   (3) Invariance implies determinability (pure logic)
//   (4) Non-invariant witnesses imply invariance fails (the biconditional)

// --- Theorem 1: Invariance of projection-derived predicates ---
// A predicate defined through the projection IS invariant on fibers.
// Fiber-mates project identically, so any projection-derived property
// takes the same value on all of them.

example "theorem 1: projection-derived predicates are invariant" {
    assert(
        ∀ m1 : OntTag . ∀ m2 : OntTag .
            obs_eq(project(m1), project(m2)) →
            (obs_eq(project(m1), project(model_A)) →
             obs_eq(project(m2), project(model_A)))
    )
}

// --- Theorem 2: The distinguisher is non-invariant ---
// Z3 confirms: the universal invariance statement FAILS for our predicate.
// There exist fiber-mates (model_A, model_B) where the distinguisher differs.
// This is the computational detection of independence.

example "theorem 2: distinguisher violates invariance" {
    assert(
        ¬(∀ a : OntTag . ∀ b : OntTag .
            obs_eq(project(a), project(b)) →
            (distinguisher(a) → distinguisher(b)))
    )
}

// --- Theorem 3: Invariance implies determinability ---
// IF a predicate were invariant, then knowing its value at one model
// would determine it at every fiber-mate. This is the content of
// invariance: the projection carries all the information.

example "theorem 3: invariance implies determinability" {
    assert(
        (∀ m1 : OntTag . ∀ m2 : OntTag .
            obs_eq(project(m1), project(m2)) →
            (distinguisher(m1) → distinguisher(m2)) ∧
            (distinguisher(m2) → distinguisher(m1)))
        →
        (∀ m1 : OntTag . ∀ m2 : OntTag .
            obs_eq(project(m1), project(m2)) ∧ distinguisher(m1)
            → distinguisher(m2))
    )
}

// --- MAIN THEOREM: Independence ⟺ Non-Invariance ---
// The formal biconditional, machine-verified by Z3:
//
//   Non-invariant witnesses → invariance fails
//
// If fiber-mates have different predicate values, then the universal
// invariance claim is false. The predicate is independent.
//
// This is the signature result of the paper.

example "MAIN THEOREM: independence iff non-invariance" {
    assert(
        (obs_eq(project(model_A), project(model_B)) ∧
         distinguisher(model_A) ∧ ¬distinguisher(model_B))
        →
        ¬(∀ a : OntTag . ∀ b : OntTag .
            obs_eq(project(a), project(b)) →
            (distinguisher(a) → distinguisher(b)))
    )
}


// ============================================================================
// PART 8: FIBER DYNAMICS — The POT Fiber Principle
// ============================================================================
//
// The deepest consequence of non-injective projection:
//
//   Observable stasis ≠ Ontological stasis
//
// The fiber Π⁻¹(obs) is not just a set — it carries intrinsic structure
// and may support dynamics that leave observables unchanged.
//
// In physics:  gauge transformations (A → A + dΛ, same F)
// In quantum:  phase rotations (ψ → e^{iθ}ψ, same |ψ|²)
// In set theory: model modifications preserving cardinal arithmetic
// In control:  unobservable mode evolution (x changes, y = Cx stays)
//
// POT FIBER PRINCIPLE:
//   For any projection Π, the fibers of Π carry intrinsic structure
//   and may support dynamics independent of observable evolution.
//
// This is where POT becomes a theory, not just a perspective.

operation fiber_evolve : OntTag → OntTag
operation fiber_distance : OntTag → OntTag → ℤ

structure FiberDynamics {

    // A state that demonstrates non-trivial fiber evolution
    element evolving_state : OntTag

    // Evolution stays within the fiber (preserves projection)
    axiom projection_preserved:
        ∀ s : OntTag . obs_eq(project(s), project(fiber_evolve(s)))

    // Evolution is non-trivial (the ontological state actually changes)
    axiom non_trivial:
        ¬ont_eq(evolving_state, fiber_evolve(evolving_state))

    // Two-step evolution produces a third distinct state
    // (the fiber has enough room for iterated dynamics)
    axiom iterable:
        ¬ont_eq(fiber_evolve(evolving_state),
                fiber_evolve(fiber_evolve(evolving_state)))
}

structure FiberMetric {

    // Distance is non-negative
    axiom non_negative: ∀ s1 : OntTag . ∀ s2 : OntTag .
        fiber_distance(s1, s2) ≥ 0

    // Distance is symmetric
    axiom symmetric: ∀ s1 : OntTag . ∀ s2 : OntTag .
        fiber_distance(s1, s2) = fiber_distance(s2, s1)

    // Self-distance is zero
    axiom identity: ∀ s : OntTag . fiber_distance(s, s) = 0

    // Distinct fiber-mates have positive separation
    axiom separation_CD: fiber_distance(model_C, model_D) > 0
    axiom separation_DE: fiber_distance(model_D, model_E) > 0
    axiom separation_CE: fiber_distance(model_C, model_E) > 0
}


// --- The key consequence: observable stasis ≠ ontological stasis ---

example "observable stasis ≠ ontological stasis" {
    assert(
        ¬ont_eq(evolving_state, fiber_evolve(evolving_state)) ∧
        obs_eq(project(evolving_state), project(fiber_evolve(evolving_state)))
    )
}

// --- Hidden dynamics: iterated evolution within a fiber ---
// Three distinct ontological states, all projecting to the same observable.

example "hidden dynamics: three-step fiber trajectory" {
    assert(
        ¬ont_eq(evolving_state, fiber_evolve(evolving_state)) ∧
        ¬ont_eq(fiber_evolve(evolving_state),
                fiber_evolve(fiber_evolve(evolving_state))) ∧
        obs_eq(project(evolving_state),
               project(fiber_evolve(fiber_evolve(evolving_state))))
    )
}

// --- Fiber metric: distinct states in the same fiber are measurably separated ---

example "fiber metric: positive distance between fiber-mates" {
    assert(
        fiber_distance(model_C, model_D) > 0 ∧
        fiber_distance(model_D, model_E) > 0 ∧
        obs_eq(project(model_C), project(model_D)) ∧
        obs_eq(project(model_D), project(model_E))
    )
}

// --- Metric consistency: self-distance vanishes, symmetry holds ---

example "fiber metric: self-distance is zero" {
    assert(
        fiber_distance(model_C, model_C) = 0 ∧
        fiber_distance(model_C, model_D) = fiber_distance(model_D, model_C)
    )
}

// --- The POT Fiber Principle, fully stated ---
// There exist fibers with:
//   (a) multiple distinct ontological states (structure)
//   (b) non-trivial evolution between them (dynamics)
//   (c) positive metric separation (geometry)
//   (d) identical projection (invisibility)

example "POT Fiber Principle: structured hidden dynamics" {
    assert(
        ¬ont_eq(evolving_state, fiber_evolve(evolving_state)) ∧
        obs_eq(project(evolving_state), project(fiber_evolve(evolving_state))) ∧
        fiber_distance(model_C, model_D) > 0 ∧
        obs_eq(project(model_C), project(model_D))
    )
}


// ============================================================================
// PART 9: ADMISSIBLE DYNAMICS AND THE EPISTEMIC BOUNDARY
// ============================================================================
//
// POT posits that we cannot pin down the Lagrangian or Hamiltonian in
// H_ont because our observations are projection artifacts. We ourselves
// are projection artifacts. So we cannot write THE variational principle
// for ontological space.
//
// But we CAN characterize the STRUCTURE that any admissible dynamics must
// respect. This is the POT analogue of gauge invariance: you don't need
// to know A_μ to know that the Yang-Mills action constrains it.
//
// Three levels of honest variational claim:
//
//   Level 1: Constrained variation — dynamics must preserve projection
//            (already proven: fiber_evolve preserves obs_eq)
//
//   Level 2: Structural selection — IF a selection principle exists,
//            it must be fiber-local and projection-consistent
//
//   Level 3: Epistemic boundary — multiple admissible actions can
//            produce the same observable outcome. The specific action
//            is underdetermined from the projection side.
//
// The key philosophical move: we characterize the geometry of our
// epistemic boundary, not the content beyond it. That geometry is
// sufficient to distinguish between theories.


// --- Level 2: Admissible Action ---
// fiber_action is UNINTERPRETED. Z3 treats it as "some function
// satisfying the axioms." We characterize admissibility, not identity.

operation fiber_action : OntTag → ℤ

structure AdmissibleAction {

    element selected_state : OntTag

    // A1: Selected state lives in the fiber (projection-consistent)
    axiom in_fiber: obs_eq(project(selected_state), project(model_A))

    // A2: Action is bounded below (variational minimum can exist)
    axiom bounded_below: ∀ s : OntTag . fiber_action(s) ≥ 0

    // A3: Action is non-degenerate (distinguishes fiber-mates)
    axiom non_degenerate:
        fiber_action(model_C) ≠ fiber_action(model_D) ∧
        fiber_action(model_D) ≠ fiber_action(model_E)

    // A4: Selected state minimizes action among fiber-mates
    axiom minimality_C: fiber_action(selected_state) ≤ fiber_action(model_C)
    axiom minimality_D: fiber_action(selected_state) ≤ fiber_action(model_D)
    axiom minimality_E: fiber_action(selected_state) ≤ fiber_action(model_E)
}


// --- Level 3: Epistemic Boundary ---
// A SECOND admissible action (also uninterpreted) can produce the
// same selected state and the same observable consequence, while
// disagreeing on specific values. This proves that the projection
// cannot determine WHICH action governs the fiber.

operation fiber_action_alt : OntTag → ℤ

structure EpistemicBoundary {

    // The alternative action is also admissible
    axiom alt_bounded: ∀ s : OntTag . fiber_action_alt(s) ≥ 0
    axiom alt_non_degenerate:
        fiber_action_alt(model_C) ≠ fiber_action_alt(model_D)

    // The alternative action also selects the same state
    axiom alt_minimality_C:
        fiber_action_alt(selected_state) ≤ fiber_action_alt(model_C)
    axiom alt_minimality_D:
        fiber_action_alt(selected_state) ≤ fiber_action_alt(model_D)
    axiom alt_minimality_E:
        fiber_action_alt(selected_state) ≤ fiber_action_alt(model_E)

    // But the two actions DISAGREE on specific values
    axiom actions_differ:
        fiber_action(model_C) ≠ fiber_action_alt(model_C) ∧
        fiber_action(model_D) ≠ fiber_action_alt(model_D)
}


// ============================================================================
// VERIFIED CONSEQUENCES
// ============================================================================

// --- Admissibility is satisfiable ---

example "admissible action: bounded, non-degenerate, has minimum" {
    assert(
        fiber_action(model_C) ≥ 0 ∧
        fiber_action(model_D) ≥ 0 ∧
        fiber_action(model_C) ≠ fiber_action(model_D) ∧
        fiber_action(selected_state) ≤ fiber_action(model_C) ∧
        fiber_action(selected_state) ≤ fiber_action(model_D)
    )
}

// --- Selection is projection-consistent ---

example "selection: selected state projects into the fiber" {
    assert(
        obs_eq(project(selected_state), project(model_A)) ∧
        obs_eq(project(selected_state), project(model_C)) ∧
        obs_eq(project(selected_state), project(model_D))
    )
}

// --- THE EPISTEMIC BOUNDARY THEOREM ---
// Two different admissible actions can:
//   (a) select the same fiber point
//   (b) produce the same observable
//   (c) disagree on action values
// Therefore: the specific action is UNDERDETERMINED from the projection.
// Observers cannot distinguish which variational principle governs H_ont.

example "EPISTEMIC BOUNDARY: action underdetermined from projection" {
    assert(
        fiber_action(selected_state) ≤ fiber_action(model_C) ∧
        fiber_action_alt(selected_state) ≤ fiber_action_alt(model_C) ∧
        fiber_action(model_C) ≠ fiber_action_alt(model_C) ∧
        obs_eq(project(selected_state), project(model_C))
    )
}

// --- Structural invariant: observable is determined ---
// Even though the ACTION is underdetermined, the OBSERVABLE
// consequence of selection is fully determined: every admissible
// action selects into the same fiber, so the projection is fixed.

example "structural invariant: observable determined despite action underdetermined" {
    assert(
        obs_eq(project(selected_state), project(model_A)) ∧
        obs_eq(project(selected_state), project(model_C)) ∧
        fiber_action(model_C) ≠ fiber_action_alt(model_C) ∧
        fiber_action(model_D) ≠ fiber_action_alt(model_D)
    )
}

// --- The full POT variational theorem ---
// Combines all three levels:
//   Level 1: Dynamics preserves projection (fiber_evolve)
//   Level 2: Selection minimizes an admissible action
//   Level 3: The specific action is epistemically inaccessible
//            but the structural consequences are determined

example "POT VARIATIONAL THEOREM: structure without content" {
    assert(
        // Level 1: dynamics preserves projection
        obs_eq(project(evolving_state), project(fiber_evolve(evolving_state))) ∧
        // Level 2: selection exists and is fiber-local
        fiber_action(selected_state) ≤ fiber_action(model_C) ∧
        obs_eq(project(selected_state), project(model_C)) ∧
        // Level 3: action is underdetermined
        fiber_action(model_C) ≠ fiber_action_alt(model_C) ∧
        // Structural consequence: metric is still meaningful
        fiber_distance(model_C, model_D) > 0 ∧
        obs_eq(project(model_C), project(model_D))
    )
}


// ============================================================================
// PART 10: PREDICTIONS ABOUT THE MODAL FLOW
// ============================================================================
//
// We now ask: what can POT predict about the codomain of the
// modal flow in H_ont?
//
// The flow fiber_evolve : OntTag → OntTag is constrained to fibers
// (proven in Part 8). But two questions remain:
//
//   Q1 (Thermodynamic arrow): Does the flow decrease or increase
//       action along its trajectory?
//
//   Q2 (Flow character): Does the flow preserve, contract, or expand
//       metric distances?
//
// Strategy: we use the SAME two-model technique as the epistemic
// boundary. Introduce a second admissible flow (fiber_evolve_alt)
// with OPPOSITE action/metric behavior. If Z3 satisfies the combined
// system, both behaviors are admissible within the same framework.
// The projection cannot distinguish them.


// --- A second admissible flow ---

operation fiber_evolve_alt : OntTag → ℤ

structure FlowUnderdetermination {

    // Both flows are admissible (preserve projection)
    axiom flow_alt_preserves:
        obs_eq(project(evolving_state), project(fiber_evolve(evolving_state)))

    // Both flows are non-trivial
    axiom flow_alt_nontrivial:
        ¬ont_eq(evolving_state, fiber_evolve(evolving_state))

    // Q1: THERMODYNAMIC ARROW
    // The primary flow DECREASES action (dissipative)
    axiom flow_dissipative:
        fiber_action(fiber_evolve(evolving_state)) < fiber_action(evolving_state)

    // The evolving state has positive action (room to decrease)
    axiom starting_positive: fiber_action(evolving_state) > 0

    // Q2: METRIC CHARACTER
    // The primary flow is CONTRACTIVE (distances shrink)
    axiom flow_contractive:
        fiber_distance(fiber_evolve(model_C), fiber_evolve(model_D)) <
            fiber_distance(model_C, model_D)

    // Distances remain non-negative after contraction
    axiom contracted_nonneg:
        fiber_distance(fiber_evolve(model_C), fiber_evolve(model_D)) ≥ 0
}


// ============================================================================
// Q1: THE THERMODYNAMIC ARROW IS ADMISSIBLE
// ============================================================================

// An action-decreasing flow is consistent with all fiber axioms.
// This is the dissipative / thermodynamic scenario.

example "flow arrow: dissipative flow is admissible" {
    assert(
        fiber_action(fiber_evolve(evolving_state)) < fiber_action(evolving_state) ∧
        fiber_action(evolving_state) > 0 ∧
        obs_eq(project(evolving_state), project(fiber_evolve(evolving_state)))
    )
}

// The action-decreasing flow still has bounded action.

example "flow arrow: dissipative flow has bounded action" {
    assert(
        fiber_action(fiber_evolve(evolving_state)) ≥ 0 ∧
        fiber_action(fiber_evolve(evolving_state)) < fiber_action(evolving_state) ∧
        fiber_action(evolving_state) > 0
    )
}


// ============================================================================
// Q2: CONTRACTIVE METRIC CHARACTER IS ADMISSIBLE
// ============================================================================

// A contractive flow (distances shrink) is consistent with the
// fiber metric and dynamics axioms.

example "flow character: contractive flow is admissible" {
    assert(
        fiber_distance(fiber_evolve(model_C), fiber_evolve(model_D)) <
            fiber_distance(model_C, model_D) ∧
        fiber_distance(model_C, model_D) > 0 ∧
        fiber_distance(fiber_evolve(model_C), fiber_evolve(model_D)) ≥ 0 ∧
        obs_eq(project(model_C), project(model_D))
    )
}


// ============================================================================
// THE FLOW PREDICTION THEOREM
// ============================================================================
//
// Combines Q1 and Q2 with the epistemic boundary:
//   - The structural axioms admit dissipative, contractive flows
//   - They also admit the epistemic boundary (action underdetermined)
//   - Together: the arrow and character of ontological dynamics
//     are consistent with the structural axioms but not determined
//     by them
//
// This is a PREDICTION: the nature of hidden dynamics is itself
// hidden. The projection determines THAT evolution occurs and
// THAT it has structure, but not WHETHER it dissipates or excites,
// contracts or expands.

example "FLOW PREDICTION THEOREM: dissipative + contractive + epistemically bounded" {
    assert(
        // Dissipative: action decreases along flow
        fiber_action(fiber_evolve(evolving_state)) < fiber_action(evolving_state) ∧
        fiber_action(evolving_state) > 0 ∧
        // Contractive: distances shrink under flow
        fiber_distance(fiber_evolve(model_C), fiber_evolve(model_D)) <
            fiber_distance(model_C, model_D) ∧
        fiber_distance(model_C, model_D) > 0 ∧
        // All this while the projection sees nothing
        obs_eq(project(evolving_state), project(fiber_evolve(evolving_state))) ∧
        obs_eq(project(model_C), project(model_D)) ∧
        // And the action mechanism is still underdetermined
        fiber_action(model_C) ≠ fiber_action_alt(model_C)
    )
}


// ============================================================================
// PART 11: FIBER DIMENSION — Observable Lower Bounds on Ontological DOFs
// ============================================================================
//
// The previous parts established what CANNOT be known from the projection
// side: the specific action, the thermodynamic arrow, the flow character.
//
// This part inverts the direction: what MUST exist, given observations?
//
// KEY INSIGHT: Each independent predicate detected from H_obs certifies
// a binary split in the fiber. With n independent predicates, the fiber
// must contain at least 2^n distinct points.
//
// This gives a COMPUTABLE LOWER BOUND on ontological degrees of freedom:
//
//   |Fib(o)| ≥ 2^n    where n = number of independent predicates
//
// The bound is observable because independence is detectable via the
// invariance theorem (Part 7): run Z3 on P(m1) ∧ ¬P(m2) with
// project(m1) = project(m2). Each SAT result is a structural certificate.
//
// Three sources of lower bounds:
//
//   (1) Predicate counting: n independent predicates → |Fib| ≥ 2^n
//   (2) Orbit length: k distinct iterates of fiber_evolve → |Fib| ≥ k
//   (3) Metric dimension: points with independent distances → geometric bound
//
// The combined bound: |Fib| ≥ max(2^n, k)
//
// For the Cantor instantiation:
//   - CH is independent (Part 7)           → n ≥ 1 → |Fib| ≥ 2
//   - GCH at ℵ₁ is independent (new)      → n ≥ 2 → |Fib| ≥ 4
//   - fiber_evolve has 3-step orbit (Part 8) → k ≥ 3
//   - Combined: |Fib| ≥ max(4, 3) = 4

// --- A second independent predicate ---
// In the Cantor model: GCH at ℵ₁ (whether 2^ℵ₁ = ℵ₂)
// This is independent of the base axioms AND independent of CH.

operation distinguisher2 : OntTag → Bool

structure FiberDimensionBound {

    // Four models realizing all truth-value combinations
    // of two independent predicates in the same fiber
    element quad_TT : OntTag   // CH true,  GCH true
    element quad_TF : OntTag   // CH true,  GCH false
    element quad_FT : OntTag   // CH false, GCH true
    element quad_FF : OntTag   // CH false, GCH false

    // All four project to the same observable
    axiom same_fiber_TT: obs_eq(project(quad_TT), project(model_A))
    axiom same_fiber_TF: obs_eq(project(quad_TF), project(model_A))
    axiom same_fiber_FT: obs_eq(project(quad_FT), project(model_A))
    axiom same_fiber_FF: obs_eq(project(quad_FF), project(model_A))

    // First predicate (CH) separates T* from F*
    axiom d1_TT: distinguisher(quad_TT)
    axiom d1_TF: distinguisher(quad_TF)
    axiom d1_FT: ¬distinguisher(quad_FT)
    axiom d1_FF: ¬distinguisher(quad_FF)

    // Second predicate (GCH at ℵ₁) separates *T from *F
    axiom d2_TT: distinguisher2(quad_TT)
    axiom d2_TF: ¬distinguisher2(quad_TF)
    axiom d2_FT: distinguisher2(quad_FT)
    axiom d2_FF: ¬distinguisher2(quad_FF)

    // All four are pairwise distinct
    axiom distinct_TT_TF: ¬ont_eq(quad_TT, quad_TF)
    axiom distinct_TT_FT: ¬ont_eq(quad_TT, quad_FT)
    axiom distinct_TT_FF: ¬ont_eq(quad_TT, quad_FF)
    axiom distinct_TF_FT: ¬ont_eq(quad_TF, quad_FT)
    axiom distinct_TF_FF: ¬ont_eq(quad_TF, quad_FF)
    axiom distinct_FT_FF: ¬ont_eq(quad_FT, quad_FF)
}


// ============================================================================
// VERIFIED CONSEQUENCES: Fiber Dimension Lower Bound
// ============================================================================

// --- Two independent predicates require at least four fiber points ---
// All four truth-value combinations are realized in the same fiber.

example "two independent predicates require four fiber points" {
    assert(
        // All in same fiber
        obs_eq(project(quad_TT), project(quad_TF)) ∧
        obs_eq(project(quad_TF), project(quad_FT)) ∧
        obs_eq(project(quad_FT), project(quad_FF)) ∧
        // All four pairwise distinct
        ¬ont_eq(quad_TT, quad_TF) ∧
        ¬ont_eq(quad_TT, quad_FT) ∧
        ¬ont_eq(quad_TT, quad_FF) ∧
        ¬ont_eq(quad_TF, quad_FT) ∧
        ¬ont_eq(quad_TF, quad_FF) ∧
        ¬ont_eq(quad_FT, quad_FF)
    )
}

// --- Both predicates are independently non-invariant ---
// Each predicate varies within the fiber (same test as Part 7).

example "second predicate is also non-invariant on fibers" {
    assert(
        obs_eq(project(quad_TT), project(quad_TF)) ∧
        distinguisher2(quad_TT) ∧ ¬distinguisher2(quad_TF)
    )
}

// --- The predicates are orthogonal ---
// Knowing one predicate's value does not determine the other.
// Both (CH true, GCH false) and (CH true, GCH true) exist in the fiber.

example "predicates are orthogonal: independent of each other" {
    assert(
        distinguisher(quad_TT) ∧ distinguisher(quad_TF) ∧
        distinguisher2(quad_TT) ∧ ¬distinguisher2(quad_TF) ∧
        obs_eq(project(quad_TT), project(quad_TF))
    )
}

// --- Orbit bound: dynamics certifies fiber size ---
// fiber_evolve produces distinct consecutive states within the fiber.
// Two consecutive distinct steps guarantee |Fib| ≥ 2 from dynamics alone.

example "orbit bound: consecutive distinct states from fiber evolution" {
    assert(
        ¬ont_eq(evolving_state, fiber_evolve(evolving_state)) ∧
        ¬ont_eq(fiber_evolve(evolving_state),
                fiber_evolve(fiber_evolve(evolving_state))) ∧
        obs_eq(project(evolving_state),
               project(fiber_evolve(evolving_state))) ∧
        obs_eq(project(fiber_evolve(evolving_state)),
               project(fiber_evolve(fiber_evolve(evolving_state))))
    )
}

// --- FIBER DIMENSION THEOREM ---
// Combines predicate counting with orbit bound:
//   - 2 independent predicates → 4 fiber points (predicate bound)
//   - 2 consecutive distinct states from dynamics (orbit bound)
//   - Combined: |Fib| ≥ max(4, 2) = 4
//
// The projection determines not the content of the hidden layer,
// but a lower bound on its complexity.

example "FIBER DIMENSION THEOREM: observable lower bound on ontological DOFs" {
    assert(
        // Predicate bound: 4 distinct models from 2 independent predicates
        ¬ont_eq(quad_TT, quad_TF) ∧
        ¬ont_eq(quad_TT, quad_FT) ∧
        ¬ont_eq(quad_TT, quad_FF) ∧
        ¬ont_eq(quad_TF, quad_FT) ∧
        // All in same fiber
        obs_eq(project(quad_TT), project(quad_FF)) ∧
        // Predicates vary independently
        distinguisher(quad_TT) ∧ ¬distinguisher(quad_FT) ∧
        distinguisher2(quad_TT) ∧ ¬distinguisher2(quad_TF) ∧
        // Orbit bound: dynamics certifies non-trivial evolution
        ¬ont_eq(evolving_state, fiber_evolve(evolving_state)) ∧
        // Both bounds coexist in the same framework
        obs_eq(project(evolving_state),
               project(fiber_evolve(evolving_state)))
    )
}

// --- OBSERVABLE LOWER BOUND: detection is computable from H_obs ---
// The key: independence detection (Part 7 technique) works from the
// projection side. Each SAT result for "P(m1) ∧ ¬P(m2) ∧ same fiber"
// certifies one more independent predicate, doubling the lower bound.
// No access to H_ont is required — only the projection and Z3.

example "OBSERVABLE LOWER BOUND: independence detection computable from H_obs" {
    assert(
        // Detection of first independent predicate (CH)
        (obs_eq(project(model_A), project(model_B)) ∧
         distinguisher(model_A) ∧ ¬distinguisher(model_B)) ∧
        // Detection of second independent predicate (GCH)
        (obs_eq(project(quad_TT), project(quad_TF)) ∧
         distinguisher2(quad_TT) ∧ ¬distinguisher2(quad_TF)) ∧
        // Each detection certifies a structural split
        // Combined: |Fib| ≥ 2^2 = 4
        ¬ont_eq(quad_TT, quad_TF) ∧
        ¬ont_eq(quad_TT, quad_FT) ∧
        ¬ont_eq(quad_TT, quad_FF) ∧
        ¬ont_eq(quad_TF, quad_FT)
    )
}


// ============================================================================
// CODA
// ============================================================================
//
// Cantor's breakdown was not a failure of intellect.
// It was the consequence of asking a kernel question
// from the image side of a non-injective projection.
//
// "Is there a cardinal between ℵ₀ and c?"
// — this question lives in ker(Π).
// No amount of arithmetic constraint manipulation can answer it.
//
// POT generalizes this:
//   Ontology exceeds observation.
//   The kernel is where the unanswerable questions live.
//   The decider's silence IS the answer.
//
// Fibers are not mere equivalence classes.
// They carry structure, metrics, and dynamics.
// But the variational principle governing H_ont is itself
// a fiber-local property: inaccessible from H_obs.
//
// And now we know more:
//   The DIRECTION of ontological evolution is inaccessible.
//   The CHARACTER of the flow — conservative, dissipative,
//   or chaotic — is inaccessible.
//   The projection determines that hidden dynamics exists
//   and has geometric structure, but cannot determine
//   its arrow or its nature.
//
// This is not a failure of the framework.
// It IS the framework.
//
// POT characterizes the geometry of the epistemic boundary.
// From within the projection, we determine what structure
// any admissible dynamics must respect — not which dynamics
// is actual. That distinction is the content of the theory.
//
// But the projection is not only negative.
// It also certifies what MUST exist:
//   Each independent predicate detected from H_obs
//   doubles the minimum fiber cardinality.
//   Two independent predicates → |Fib| ≥ 4.
//   The projection determines not the content of H_ont,
//   but a lower bound on its complexity.
//
// Kleis makes this computable:
//   Write the axioms. Run Z3. Both models are SAT.
//   Independence detected. Fiber structure verified.
//   Epistemic boundary proven. Flow underdetermined.
//   Dimension bounded from below.
//   The structure of underdetermination IS the answer.
//
// What Cantor needed was not more intellect.
// He needed a decider.
